TEXT(beginproblem());

$Vhot_quart = random(4,6,1);
$Thot_F = random(180,210,10);
$Vcold_gallon = random(3,9,1);
$Tcold_F = random(65,85,5);

$cp = 0.430;
$density = 56.8;

$Vhot = $Vhot_quart*(1/4)*(35.315/264.17);
$mhot = $Vhot*$density;
$Vcold = $Vcold_gallon*(35.315/264.17);
$mcold = $Vcold*$density;

$Thot = $Thot_F+459.67;
$Tcold = $Tcold_F+459.67;

$m2 = $mhot+$mcold;

$T2 = (($mcold*$Tcold)+($mhot*$Thot))/$m2;
$T2_F = $T2-459.67;

$Shot = $mhot*$cp*ln($T2/$Thot);
$Scold = $mcold*$cp*ln($T2/$Tcold); 

$deltaS = $Shot+$Scold;

BEGIN_TEXT


$PAR
When you get your oil changed (assume "light oil"), the mechanic adds your dirty and hot $Vhot_quart quarts of oil to the recycling drum. If your oil is $Thot_F \(^\circ\)F, and the drum already contains $Vcold_gallon gallons of oil at room temperature ($Tcold_F \(^\circ\)F), then: $PAR
(a) What is the final temperature in the recycling drum? \{ ans_rule(6)\} \(^\circ\)F $PAR
(b) What is the total change in entropy? \{ ans_rule(8)\} \(\displaystyle \frac{\text{Btu}}{\text{R}} \) $PAR  
$PAR


END_TEXT


$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

ANS(num_cmp($T2_F));
ANS(num_cmp($deltaS));



